Non-obvious decisions for task 6:

**Why extend the existing /v1/chat/completions handler vs. write a new one.**
The old handler already had 70% of what ADR-023 §6 requires: agent_id
extraction, degraded-model swap, routing to LlmRouter. Creating a second
endpoint would've duplicated most of that. The risk was that "extending"
quietly changes semantics for existing callers — so I kept the behavior
for non-auth'd requests (no agent_id → pass through unchanged, no
usage recorded) as a compatibility guarantee. Anthropic /v1/messages is
untouched; it's got its own complex proxy path.

**Why `Authorization: Bearer sk-{agent}` not a custom header.**
Harnesses expect an OpenAI-style endpoint. `Authorization: Bearer sk-...`
is what OpenAI's SDK sends. Making agents use a custom `X-Agent-Id`
header would force each harness vendor to special-case xpressclaw; the
`sk-{agent}` trick piggybacks on convention. Real provider keys never
reach this endpoint (ADR-023 §6 forbids harnesses holding them), so the
ambiguity never arises in practice.

**The `.filter(|s| !s.contains("xpressclaw"))` heuristic.**
Kept from the pre-existing code — it guards against a real provider key
that happens to start with `sk-` accidentally being treated as an agent
name. The word "xpressclaw" appears in one specific real key pattern
the codebase has encountered. Fragile, but removing it is a separate
bug-risk and outside this task's scope. If/when we move to first-class
agent auth (JWT? OAuth?) this goes away.

**Budget check semantics: three return states of check_budget()**
- `Ok(true)`  — under budget, allow.
- `Ok(false)` — over budget but `on_exceeded: alert` — log and allow.
- `Err(_)`    — paused, OR `on_exceeded: stop` over limit. Refuse with 429.

Mapping `Err` to 429 (not 402 / 403) because "Too Many Requests" is the
closest HTTP semantic to "budget exhausted for now, try later." OpenAI
clients tend to retry on 429 with backoff, which is the right behavior
when the daily limit auto-resets at midnight.

**Why the streaming path counts chars/4, not tokens.**
`ChatCompletionChunk` has no usage field — the router trait doesn't
expose terminal usage on streams. Getting accurate per-provider usage
requires either extending the chunk type or writing a per-provider
post-stream hook. Both are bigger than this task's scope. chars/4 is a
known-bad approximation but it's non-zero and directional — an agent
that streams twice as much gets charged twice as much. When task 11
lands this becomes real.

**Why record_usage is fire-and-forget.**
A failed usage write shouldn't fail the request — the user already got
their completion, penalizing them by returning an error would be rude.
Worst case we lose a row of spending data; the next request with real
usage will re-assert the budget state. Logged at warn level for
observability.

**Canned provider test pattern.**
I built a minimal `CannedProvider` implementing LlmProvider directly in
the test module rather than mocking at the HTTP layer. Tests the real
routing path (LlmRouter → provider) end-to-end. Much faster than
spinning up a mock HTTP server, and the provider trait boundary is
exactly where the ADR-023 sidecar lives.

**Seeding `degraded_model` via raw SQL in the test.**
The BudgetManager doesn't expose a public "set degraded_model for test"
method, so I insert into the `budget_state` table directly. This is
acceptable in a test but would be a smell in real code — it bypasses
the on_exceeded workflow that would normally set degraded_model in
production. If BudgetManager grows a test seam later, migrate this
test off the raw SQL.
